Aloha Poke gets it right. They start by offering you a choice of white rice, brown rice or mixed greens. Then you get a choice of Ahi Tuna, Salmon or Tofu, all of which can be marinated or 'naked'. After that you choose the ingredients that you want including, cucumber, onion, seaweed, edamame, scallion, avocado and more. Finally the sauce - Samurai, Aioli, wasabi and more. It's  all mixed up in a bowls that come in three sizes, 8 oz, 16 oz or 24 oz. The result is a motley but delicious blend of textures and flavors.  This is a Hawaiian creation of course pineapple is offered as an ingredient. The bowls are prepared I think at just below room temperature so the mix seems to work even better. This is the meal or snack that you need but you didn't  know it.  All of the workers there are great. They are friendly, helpful and enthusiastic . They are second to none. If you're from Hawaii, forget everything you know about poke bowls from back home, and you'll learn to love these for what they are. You will have a hard time finding comparable traditional poke bowls here unless you spend the extra time customizing your order (i.e., removing most of the ingredients from the preset bowls or just starting from scratch) in your head while waiting in line.  Poke as a mainland "health food" trend in general continues to baffle me, but it still hits the spot when you're really craving a poke bowl and can't fly home anytime soon. As far as I know, Aloha Poke was the first to introduce and capitalize on this trend here in Chicago at the French Market earlier this year (or at least they're the ones to really have grabbed the spotlight) and as a result, has been able to rapidly grow with several locations in less than a year.  Although some may argue this (and every other place like it) is borderline cultural appropriation, I'd say it's pretty damn good once you accept the fact this is what a poke bowl on the mainland is supposed to be.
